---
import ContentPage from '../../layouts/ContentPage.astro';

const description =
  'A short, fixed-scope review before you spend real money on AI. Use cases, cost, and whether an agent even makes sense. Usually 1-2 weeks.';

const jsonLd = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@graph': [
    {
      '@type': 'Service',
      '@id': 'https://larsullrich.de/services/readiness-audit/#service',
      name: 'Readiness & Production Audit',
      url: 'https://larsullrich.de/services/readiness-audit/',
      description,
      provider: { '@id': 'https://larsullrich.de/#person' },
      areaServed: ['DE', 'EU', 'Worldwide'],
      serviceType: 'AI readiness and production audit',
    },
    {
      '@type': 'FAQPage',
      mainEntity: [
        {
          '@type': 'Question',
          name: 'How long is the Readiness & Production Audit?',
          acceptedAnswer: {
            '@type': 'Answer',
            text: 'Fixed scope, usually 1-2 weeks.',
          },
        },
        {
          '@type': 'Question',
          name: 'What do I leave with?',
          acceptedAnswer: {
            '@type': 'Answer',
            text: 'A shortlist of use cases worth doing, a clear build / buy / skip call, a cost picture you can argue with, and an EU AI Act check when it matters.',
          },
        },
      ],
    },
  ],
};
---

<ContentPage
  title="Readiness & Production Audit - Lars Ullrich"
  description={description}
  canonical="/services/readiness-audit/"
  noteId="readiness-audit"
  heading="Readiness & Production Audit"
  eyebrow="Service"
  lead="You're under pressure to do something with AI. Cool. Let's figure out what actually earns its keep before you fund a build."
  icon="/graphics/icon-signal-nodes.svg"
  ctaLabel="Talk about an audit"
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
>
  <p>
    I run this as a fixed-scope engagement. Usually one to two weeks. We look at your product, your data, and your stack. Then we pick a few bets that could pay for themselves.
  </p>

  <h2>What we dig into</h2>
  <p>
    Which use cases are real, and which are slide theater. Whether an agent helps or just makes a mess. Build it, buy it, or leave it alone, with reasons you can take into a meeting. A rough cost model so nobody is guessing. And if you're in the EU, an
    <a href="/eu-ai-act-readiness/">AI Act check</a>
    when the system might fall in scope.
  </p>

  <h2>What you walk away with</h2>
  <p>
    A write-up and a short readout. Prioritized shortlist. Recommendation. Risks. Next step. If that next step is a build, it feeds a
    <a href="/#services">Build Sprint</a>.
    If you already shipped something shaky, look at the
    <a href="/agent-reliability/">Reliability Retainer</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>When this is the right move</h2>
  <p>
    Start here when the room is still arguing about AI in the abstract. If you already know the thing to build, skip ahead. If you need someone in the seat longer term, that's
    <a href="/fractional-cto-caio/">fractional CTO / CAIO</a>.
    For how this shows up in the wild, see
    <a href="/work/patterns/">engagement patterns</a>.
  </p>
</ContentPage>
